"{\"uid\": \"thesouthafrican.com-sport-paris-olympics-2024-video-will-chad-le-clos-retire-after-olympic-devastation\", \"text\": \"Copyright Blue Sky Publications (Pty) Ltd. All Rights Reserved.  thesouthafrican.com is a division of Blue Sky Publications Ltd. Reproduction without permission prohibited  Home\\u00bbSport\\u00bbParis Olympics 2024\\u00bbVIDEO: Will Chad le Clos retire after Olympic 'devastation'?  Chad le Clos bowed out of the Paris Olympic Games on Friday. Will this bring an end to his illustrious career?  All eyes - from a South African perspective - were on Chad le Clos as he took part in his first heat at the Olympics on Friday, and he ultimately managed to finish in second.  However, his time of52:24subsequently proved to befar off the mark. Le Clos, who was battling a shoulder injury in the lead-up to the Games, was24th fastest overall in the 40-swimmer strong field.  \\\"I suffered a shoulder tear four weeks ago when a kid jumped on me when I was swimming and my shoulder popped out,\\\" he toldTeam SA's website before the swim.  \\\"It will have recovered but the inflammation and damage done has affected me. Three weeks ago I was crying every day. I will be devastated if I can not compete\\u2026 it will be one of the worst moments in my career.  \\\"I have put so much into it. I am now 32, a ballie, a pensioner in swimming terms. My body feels like it's 40. I have bled for this sport, bled for my country. I am a patriot.\\\"  Unfortunately, the worst-case scenario played out for Le Clos, who could be seen rubbing his shoulder immediately after the race - clearly in discomfort.  Although this result almost certainly brings Le Clos' Olympic career to an end,  before this race, he made it clear that he wasn't ready to retire.  In fact, the 32-year-old had said he was even targeting possible involvement in the 2026 Commonwealth Games.  \\\"I have always wanted to go down as the best. Have I under-achieved? No. I have over-achieved. Let us play this back. From 2012 I over-achieved. I beat Phelps. I had the world at my feet. I followed up by winning double gold at the 2013 world championships. At the 2014 Commonwealth Games I won seven medals. In 2015 at the world champs I won gold and silver. At Rio 2016 the silver should have been gold.  \\\"In 2017 I was world champ again and at the 2018 Commonwealth Games I won five medals. I have also won 20 world short-course championship medals, the second most in the history of swimming. Only Ryan Lochte has won more and I need three more medals (or two gold) to overtake him as short-course swimming GOAT. Then you have Phelps and myself as swimming's two GOATS. How could that be under-achieving?  \\\"I think people tend to look at the Olympics every four years and forget everything else. As I said, with respect, I am a pensioner. I know I will have to make a decision as to when to stop, but my immediate future after Paris is breaking Lochte's all-time record at the world short-course championships in Budapest in December. Then, it would be the 2026 Commonwealth Games. I have already won 18 medals there, even more than Ian Thorpe. Who knows what happens after that?\\\"  WIN R2 000: Take The South African's SASSA Survey  The South African is hiring! Freelance writing positions available  Follow The South African on Facebook for the latest local and international news  Follow The South African's WhatsApp channel for the latest sport, lifestyle and local news  Follow The South African on X for the latest, breaking news  A brand new shopping mall is coming to Pretoria East, bringing major retailers and new convenience to the area.  Orlando Pirates are reportedly set to welcome a new staff member in former Stellenbosch FC Head of Recruitment Brendon Fourie.  Masindi Nemtajela was stretched off during Orlando Pirates' 6-0 win over TS Galaxy on Sunday afternoon in Mbombela.  IT support is not just technical, it is personal.  Liema Pantsi's victory was clouded as fans of the 'Big Brother Mzansi' show expressed that Smash Afrika was unprofessional towards her.  A dominant weekend for the SA teams in the URC has made a big impact on the latest log standings as the playoffs edge closer.    TheSouthAfrican.com is all about South Africa and the stories that affect South Africans, wherever they are in the world.  We are independent.No agenda.No bias.  Our offices are for administrative purposes only, no visitors will be accepted without an appointment.  South Africa- Blue Sky Publications (Pty) Ltd - Registration Number: 2005/028472/07 - Address: Regus Business Centre, 1st Floor, Block B, North Park, Black River Park, 2 Fir Street, Observatory, Cape Town, 7925, South Africa  Copyright Blue Sky Publications (Pty) Ltd. All Rights Reserved.\"}"